text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!SignLanguage]]%0a%0a!Nicaraguan Sign Language%0a%0a:Author: vincent_c%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aThe Birth of a New Language%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aI first learned about Nicaraguan sign language and its development through a recent Youtube video (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1xd3IdYXdow&ab_channel=HalfasInteresting). The language developed naturally with no outside guidance starting in the 1970s in Nicaragua. Prior to the 1970s, deaf individuals in Nicaragua had very little contact with each other, and it wasn't until the first deaf schools were opened that deaf kids could interact with each other. The teachers' attempts at teaching lipreading, spoken Spanish, and basic sign language for spelling failed, but the students rapidly developed their own sign language to communicate with each other. With a large disconnect in communication between school staff and the students, American sign linguist Judy Kegl was contacted, and she began analyzing the language the children had created. She noted that younger children had taken the simpler pidgin-like language of the older students and added further complexity.%0a%0aNow known as Idioma de Señas de Nicaragua, the language was a very unique studying experience in the world of linguistics, as it was the first time a completely new, spontaneous language could be analyzed. It serves as proof, for some linguists, that language acquisition is an innate ability for humans.%0a%0aSource: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nicaraguan_Sign_Language%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 210508-013116-288550#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Home sign %0a-> - Thomas_M%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aUpon further investigation on this topic, it seems like deaf children inventing their own form of non-verbal communication is a fairly well-documented phenomenon, referred to as "home sign". Many deaf children who are not offered the support to learn, for example, ASL, rather develop their own system of communication. Home sign is more reliant on "gestures" than "signs", and thus it is still up for debate whether these systems adhere to the distinct grammatical rules of most languages. However, most home signs fade when entering adulthood and are not shared by a group, usually just one household. So, it is quite interesting that Nicaraguan sign language was able to develop in a similar fashion, but be maintained because of the greater number of kids in the same situation.%0a%0aSources:%0ahttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Home_sign%0ahttps://www.taylorfrancis.com/chapters/mono/10.4324/9780429020872-7/homesign-systems-joseph-hill-diane-lillo-martin-sandra-wood%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210508-013116-288550#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: C:)%0a(:Category: SignLanguage:)
