diff:1620437476:1620431232:=49,61c49%0a%3c #foxbegin 210508-013116-288550#%0a%3c (:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a%3c !!!Home sign %0a%3c -> - Thomas_M%0a%3c (:div1end:) %0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%3c Upon further investigation on this topic, it seems like deaf children inventing their own form of non-verbal communication is a fairly well-documented phenomenon, referred to as "home sign". Many deaf children who are not offered the support to learn, for example, ASL, rather develop their own system of communication. Home sign is more reliant on "gestures" than "signs", and thus it is still up for debate whether these systems adhere to the distinct grammatical rules of most languages. However, most home signs fade when entering adulthood and are not shared by a group, usually just one household. So, it is quite interesting that Nicaraguan sign language was able to develop in a similar fashion, but be maintained because of the greater number of kids in the same situation.%0a%3c %0a%3c Sources:%0a%3c https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Home_sign%0a%3c https://www.taylorfrancis.com/chapters/mono/10.4324/9780429020872-7/homesign-systems-joseph-hill-diane-lillo-martin-sandra-wood%0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c #foxend 210508-013116-288550#%0a---%0a> %0a
